    {
        "content": "<p><span aria-label=\"clap\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f44f\" role=\"img\" title=\"clap\">:clap:</span> (sorry Bart, I can't get on zoom)</p>",
        "id": 200097988,
        "sender_full_name": "Robert Furber",
        "timestamp": 1591623457
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ah, it doesn't look like Bart Jacobs is here on the zulip :( . I was definitely curious about the quantum case, even for qubits. Does anyone know if Bart said he knew what the objects and maps were but he was not sure about whether a universal property holds or not? It's difficult to use the Kleisli category in the quantum setting, but one might be able to work more directly with CPU maps instead? I wonder what all the data would be...</p>",
        "id": 200100551,
        "sender_full_name": "Arthur Parzygnat",
        "timestamp": 1591624665
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Hi Arthur, Do you know the literature on quantum de Finetti? One option would be to consider a diagram <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>:</mo><mrow><mi>I</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow><mo>→</mo><mrow><mi>F</mi><mi>d</mi><mi>C</mi><mi>S</mi><mi>t</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>r</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X: \\mathit{Inj} \\to \\mathit{FdCStar}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8777699999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathit\">I</span><span class=\"mord mathit\">n</span><span class=\"mord mathit\">j</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathit\">F</span><span class=\"mord mathit\">d</span><span class=\"mord mathit\">C</span><span class=\"mord mathit\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathit\">t</span><span class=\"mord mathit\">a</span><span class=\"mord mathit\">r</span></span></span></span></span> given by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>A</mi><mrow><mo>⊗</mo><mi>n</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X(n)=A^{\\otimes n}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">n</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.771331em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">A</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.771331em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">⊗</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault mtight\">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> for some algebra <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">A</span></span></span></span>, and see if it has a colimit in CPU? Here <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>I</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathit{Inj}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8777699999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathit\">I</span><span class=\"mord mathit\">n</span><span class=\"mord mathit\">j</span></span></span></span></span> is natural numbers and injections.</p>",
        "id": 200102987,
        "sender_full_name": "Sam Staton",
        "timestamp": 1591625727
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks, Sam. I'm aware of the existence of a quantum de Finetti theorem, but have not learned it yet. I suspect it would encode states as well.</p>",
        "id": 200104074,
        "sender_full_name": "Arthur Parzygnat",
        "timestamp": 1591626172
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>A good reference on the quantum deFinetti theorem is this article from 2001<br>\nCarlton M. Caves, Christopher A. Fuchs, Ruediger Schack<br>\nUnknown Quantum States: The Quantum de Finetti Representation<br>\nJ. Math. Phys. 43, 4537 (2002)<br>\narXiv:quant-ph/0104088 (quant-ph)<br>\nIt is more straightforward than the approach taken by earlier work on the subject by Hudson and Moody (Z. Wahrschein. verw. Geb. 33, 343 (1976))</p>",
        "id": 200105112,
        "sender_full_name": "Rob Spekkens",
        "timestamp": 1591626602
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks <span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"296639\">Arthur Parzygnat</span>, <span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"309133\">Rob Spekkens</span>, I think the Hudson/Moody set-up is indeed talking about a cone over this <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>I</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>j</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathit{Inj}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8777699999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathit\">I</span><span class=\"mord mathit\">n</span><span class=\"mord mathit\">j</span></span></span></span></span>-indexed diagram <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>⇉</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>⊗</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>⇉</mo><msup><mi>A</mi><mrow><mo>⊗</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>⇉</mo><mo>…</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A\\rightrightarrows A\\otimes A\\rightrightarrows A^{\\otimes 3}\\rightrightarrows \\dots </annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.86413em;vertical-align:-0.1808em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel amsrm\">⇉</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.76666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⊗</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.86413em;vertical-align:-0.1808em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel amsrm\">⇉</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9949079999999999em;vertical-align:-0.1808em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">A</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">⊗</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">3</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel amsrm\">⇉</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.12em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"minner\">…</span></span></span></span> in the category of CPU maps, with apex <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68889em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span></span></span></span></span>. Whether the theorem is saying that this diagram has a colimit in a category of C star/W star-algebras would be a bit of work to check, but it would be interesting to know.</p>",
        "id": 200118710,
        "sender_full_name": "Sam Staton",
        "timestamp": 1591631768
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Sam, see here: <a href=\"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022123669900500\">https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022123669900500</a></p>",
        "id": 200120357,
        "sender_full_name": "Robert Furber",
        "timestamp": 1591632465
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Also Sam, taking colimits in W-star-algebras is very much <em>unlike</em> doing it for C*-algebras - see my post here: <a href=\"https://mathoverflow.net/a/284325\">https://mathoverflow.net/a/284325</a></p>\n<p>I can explain somewhere else what thing is analogous to taking the limit in measure spaces, if you want.</p>",
        "id": 200121364,
        "sender_full_name": "Robert Furber",
        "timestamp": 1591632942
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Hi <span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"309635\">Robert Furber</span>! Are you saying that the categorical fact is basically in Størmer's paper, or just that someone who wants to work it out should read that first? <br>\nI agree it might be best to use W star algebras, thanks for the pointer.</p>",
        "id": 200124201,
        "sender_full_name": "Sam Staton",
        "timestamp": 1591634300
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Sam, I was trying to say the opposite-  you don't want to take the colimit in W-star-algebras - the W-star-algebra you do want is not the colimit. In that specific example, the W*-algebra we want is L^\\infty(2^\\omega) with the coin-flipping measure, but we _don't_ get anything like that - we get a W*-algebra with no normal representation on a separable Hilbert space. I have tried to explain this to many people, but my words are always misinterpreted.</p>",
        "id": 200125705,
        "sender_full_name": "Robert Furber",
        "timestamp": 1591635063
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"308397\">@Sam Staton</span>  Regarding the Størmer paper - what he proves is that the compact convex set of states on an infinite tensor product of a unital C*-algebra A (e.g. M_2) that are invariant under finite permutations is isomorphic to the Radon measures on the state space of A (not easy to explain this in the chat). Of course, it is not just any old isomorphism, but the one that comes from mapping a state \\rho to \\rho \\otimes \\rho ... and extending by convexity and continuity.</p>",
        "id": 200126758,
        "sender_full_name": "Robert Furber",
        "timestamp": 1591635561
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"308397\">@Sam Staton</span> The quantum de Finetti papers suggested by Rob Spekkens prove sharper statements because they actually deal with the finite-dimensional approximation part of the problem, and this is something that I think genuinely occurs in practice (applications of quantum de Finetti to quantum protocols). But the Størmer paper is closer to doing it by taking a colimit.</p>",
        "id": 200130689,
        "sender_full_name": "Robert Furber",
        "timestamp": 1591637459
    },
